06:21.500 --> 06:23.100
And here are your hosts.

06:27.420 --> 06:36.580
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Bander Snatch, science fiction author Kevin
O'Donnell Jr.'s first novel, made its paperback appearance in 1979. The first

06:36.580 --> 06:44.460
half of Bander Snatch depicts a 22nd century America deeply divided between the
haves and the have-nots. A burgeoning bureaucracy strangles the have-nots. In

06:44.460 --> 06:52.200
five of O'Donnell's novels, the protagonist must contend with stultifying
bureaucracies. When we ask O'Donnell if this represents a personal view, this is

06:52.200 --> 07:08.980
what he told us. I really see it happening not only here, but pretty much
everywhere where governments have been in power for any length of time. I think

07:08.980 --> 07:22.580
it's the nature of the beast, a bureaucracy of any sort, whether it's
governmental, corporate, academic. In fact, it achieves a goal beyond its stated

07:22.580 --> 07:38.300
purpose. It acquires a new goal. And that goal is to survive, to perpetuate
itself, to expand, to get fat and strong and secure. It goes all the way back to

07:38.300 --> 07:43.420
Parkinson's Law. Work expands until the time available, and when it has, you
hire two assistants.

07:46.140 --> 08:00.900
I think this is an inevitable trend in any bureaucracy, whether it's Western
-style capitalism or Maoist communism. You know, one of Mao's big campaigns was

08:00.900 --> 08:12.280
against bureaucracy. He was constantly railing against the way that no matter
what he said, no matter what he did, the bureaucracy kept growing, and it kept

08:12.280 --> 08:22.860
issuing new regulations and new rules, and here he was, the most powerful man in
China, and he couldn't affect the bureaucracy. So yeah, that's a very personal

08:22.860 --> 08:30.900
sore point with me. A primitive planet is the setting for the second half of
Bander Snatch. In a climactic struggle, the protagonist, also known as

08:30.900 --> 08:38.940
Bander Snatch, kills a monstrous bear-like alien which has attacked him. Then he
discovers the alien has a young cub, which for some reason befriends him and

08:38.940 --> 08:48.260
becomes his sidekick. O'Donnell told us that the appearance and character of the
cub were unplanned. It just sprang into being. Baby Bear actually came about

08:48.260 --> 08:58.540
almost entirely by accident. I had had, you know, Bander Snatch wandering through
this alien jungle.

09:01.860 --> 09:17.740
And I realized he needed like a, the way the story was going, he had to have
this climactic battle sequence with a natural force, some sort of wild animal.

09:18.280 --> 09:24.260
And I hadn't had any wild animals in there really big enough for him.

09:27.320 --> 09:41.040
All of a sudden, off the page came this monstrous bear-like animal that almost
loomed up before him and started attacking him. And, well, he won. And there I

09:41.040 --> 09:51.760
was with a dead bear on the ground. And just sort of somehow my fingers kept
going. And there was a sound from the distance. And it was the cub. And the next

09:51.760 --> 10:03.320
thing I knew, he had a sidekick, as you put it. That was just accidental,
really. Sidekicks are common in science fiction and fantasy. Here O'Donnell

10:03.320 --> 10:09.860
comments on the role of a sidekick. I think it helps when the protagonist has a
sidekick of some sort.

10:13.040 --> 10:26.640
When you're writing science fiction, well, you know, why not give the hero an
alien sidekick, Sam in the McGill Feighan series? I think it lets you do a little

10:26.640 --> 10:39.660
exploring into alien psychology. And at the same time, it lets you keep making
sort of mirror-like observations of human culture. More with Kevin O'Donnell Jr.

10:39.680 --> 10:40.460
on our next show.

10:47.640 --> 10:55.460
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:55.460 --> 10:56.220
Odessa, Texas.

