12:13.740 --> 12:21.740
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Kevin O'Donnell Jr.'s science fiction novel,
War of Omission, was published in 1982. In the book, O'Donnell describes a

12:21.740 --> 12:29.560
violent revolution which takes place in late 20th century America. This
revolution begins in the Northeast. O'Donnell presents the thoughts and actions

12:29.560 --> 12:38.600
of the participants on both sides of the revolution. We asked him what he was
trying to get across in War of Omission. The modern-day recapitulation of the

12:38.600 --> 12:43.260
statement that power corrupts, and absolute power corrupts absolutely.

12:47.580 --> 12:59.900
I was trying to say, hey, it's real easy to say that the system stinks and we'll
wipe it out. But what happens when you do wipe it out? You know, I think this is

12:59.900 --> 13:10.040
where every revolutionary since, you know, the French in 1787 has screwed up
thoroughly. They say, well, you know, the present system is corrupt and it's

13:10.040 --> 13:21.180
bloated and it stinks and let's throw it out and we'll have paradise. I think
that's stupid. I'm not a defender of the system. But I think the sort of

13:21.180 --> 13:33.780
sweeping burn it down just doesn't work because, you know, you wind up building
on rubble. You don't move into a structure that you can clean up and straighten

13:33.780 --> 13:44.640
out. I mean, you've got ashes. And I think really those two things were what the
book was all about. The science fictional element in War of Omission is the

13:44.640 --> 13:53.300
tisser, a weapon the revolutionaries perfect which wipes out all objects in the
target area instantaneously. It makes these objects disappear. Right, but it

13:53.300 --> 14:00.680
does something else as well. It wipes out the memory of the target area from
everyone's minds. So if a person's house and family were deleted by a tisser,

14:00.940 --> 14:07.820
neither he nor anyone else would have any memory of them. Most of the action,
especially tisser deletions, takes place in New Haven, the city where O'Donnell

14:07.820 --> 14:19.400
now lives. We asked O'Donnell if he enjoyed writing scenes in which New Haven
gets destroyed. That generated an interesting sidelight. I was sort of offended

14:19.400 --> 14:30.120
by my publisher that they cut some references in there. We have a building here
in town. It's the Knights of Columbus building, and I think it's possibly the

14:30.120 --> 14:43.260
ugliest structure ever erected anywhere in America. It's a huge, towering, ugly
brick building with massive

14:43.260 --> 14:58.180
turrets at each of the four corners of the building. I mean, it looks like it
was designed to hold off an attack by maddened archers. And I took great

14:58.180 --> 15:06.780
pleasure in destroying that in the book, having it totally obliterated from the
face of the earth. And at one point I had a character bring it back and change

15:06.780 --> 15:18.540
his mind. It was so ugly. But the editor took that, cut it right out. Nope,
sorry, can't do that. But it was fun taking out the rest of New Haven. The

15:18.540 --> 15:26.720
concept of the tisser is the heart of War of Omission. O'Donnell told us he put
a lot of effort to make the tisser believable. Well, the hardest part was trying

15:26.720 --> 15:39.900
to make it plausible. And a review or two has appeared that, you know, has
really faulted the book on those grounds. But, you know, for whatever reason

15:39.900 --> 15:52.020
that person just did not believe the tisser. And I put so much effort into
trying to make it believable. I think I put more effort into that than any other

15:52.020 --> 16:03.120
part of the book. Trying to make it seem very natural. And trying to provide
possible explanations for why this happened. Sort of brief meditations on the

16:03.120 --> 16:16.520
nature of reality. For those who accepted the explanation, who believed the
tisser, I think the book worked. And I think if you can't believe it, the book

16:16.520 --> 16:25.220
just falls flat. The tisser is believable, and War of Omission works. We'll look
at Kevin O'Donnell Jr.'s Journeys of McGill Feighan series on our next show.

16:32.220 --> 16:40.100
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show. A production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association. Produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:40.100 --> 17:10.640
Odessa, Texas. 

17:48.220 --> 17:53.380
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show. A commentary on science fiction and
